abstract: As MediaStorm celebrates 10 years, its founder looks ahead to the challenges and opportunities facing photographers in the online world.
snippet: As MediaStorm celebrates 10 years, its founder looks ahead to the challenges and opportunities facing photographers in the online world.
lead_paragraph: Brian Storm was raised in the Detroit area and attended the College of the Ozarks on a baseball scholarship. While obtaining a graduate degree at the University of Missouri’s School of Journalism in 1993, he discovered computers and began making interactive CD-ROM disks. He started a company, MediaStorm, but put it on hold while working for MSNBC and Corbis over the next decade.He relaunched MediaStorm in 2005 as a film-production company and interactive design studio, which this month celebrates its 10th anniversary. He spoke with James Estrin about the future of photography and multimedia. Their conversation has been edited.

abstract: As capable as Mercedes-Benz AMG and BMW M cars, ATS-V is letter-perfect in its driving dynamics. Now, if Cadillac can get enthusiasts to understand that.
snippet: As capable as Mercedes-Benz AMG and BMW M cars, ATS-V is letter-perfect in its driving dynamics. Now, if Cadillac can get enthusiasts to understand that.
lead_paragraph: LETTERS can be so meaningful. M affixed to a BMW or AMG on a Mercedes-Benz seduces performance enthusiasts. The V, found on Cadillac, is the last of them alphabetically but possibly Speed Racer’s first consonant of choice. Seriously. The ATS-V sedan and coupe, built to take on C63, M3 and M4, is the real deal for taming tarmac. If only Cadillac had street cred.

abstract: TransCanada asked the Obama administration to halt its review of the project, a delay that would almost certainly put off a final decision until President Obama left office.
snippet: TransCanada asked the Obama administration to halt its review of the project, a delay that would almost certainly put off a final decision until President Obama left office.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The company seeking to build the Keystone XL oil pipeline asked the Obama administration on Monday to suspend its yearslong review of the project, potentially bringing an abrupt halt to a politically charged debate that had become part of a broader struggle over President Obama’s environmental policies.

headline_main: Supreme Court to Decide if Georgia Went Too Far in Excluding Black Jurors
headline_print_headline: Justices Hear Bias Case on Excluding Black Jurors

abstract: Far too many prosecutors exploit peremptory challenges to create racially unrepresentative juries and win convictions.
snippet: Far too many prosecutors exploit peremptory challenges to create racially unrepresentative juries and win convictions.
lead_paragraph: One prospective juror did not make enough eye contact. Another appeared nervous and confused. A third had a son who was close in age to the defendant. A fourth was involved with the Head Start program.

abstract: Plus: questions about being recruited for cosmetic procedures, dogs at funerals, and moms who like to hang out with teenagers.
snippet: Plus: questions about being recruited for cosmetic procedures, dogs at funerals, and moms who like to hang out with teenagers.
lead_paragraph: The mother of my son’s classmate invited my son and me to their home. We had a nice time. She invited me for a walk the next day, and the four of us hung out several times. Later, she told me her son has autism, which she asked me to keep secret. After that, she started texting and calling several times a week, often asking favors: Could I watch her son? Could I help at her party? I began pulling back, but she didn’t notice. So, the next few times she called, I said we were busy. This ended the relationship, but I feel guilty. Should I have handled this differently?

abstract: This Michigan city is a place people leave. So when international students show up, arms open.
snippet: This Michigan city is a place people leave. So when international students show up, arms open.
lead_paragraph: A few months after Abhishek Y. Utekar left Mumbai, India, to start an M.B.A. program at the University of Michigan campus in Flint, his landlord gave him a driving tour of his new home. Dennis Brownfield watched out for his tenants, and he wanted Mr. Utekar to understand the dynamics of a city often defined by deindustrialization and decay. His car provided the first lesson. It was a Honda Civic with a license plate that read “GM LEFT,” a commentary on the 70,000 automotive jobs that have disappeared over the years in this birthplace of General Motors.
